No features are detected when there is an absence of cells. Where no channel is found, the origin of the error is not clear, as these often have many cells in view. In these cases, hdf5 output file is furthermore tiny (~15Kb).

# select interesting features
df_feats = fr.data[[
    'well',
    'field',
    'cell_index',
    'primary__primary4_roisize',
    'primary__primary4_n2_avg',
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_1',
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_2',
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_3',
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_5',
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_7',
    'tertiary__expanded_spotfeatures_avg_intensity',
    'tertiary__expanded_n2_avg',
    'tertiary__expanded_spotfeatures_count',
    'content',
    'moa']].copy(deep=True)

# rewrite column headers
df_feats = df_feats.rename(columns={
    'cell_index' : 'cell count',
    'primary__primary4_roisize' : 'roi size',  # nuclear size
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_1' : 'granulometry (1)',  # granulometry level 1
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_2' : 'granulometry (2)',  # granulometry level 2
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_3' : 'granulometry (3)',  # granulometry level 3
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_5' : 'granulometry (5)',  # granulometry level 5
    'tertiary__expanded_granu_open_volume_7' : 'granulometry (7)',  # granulometry level 7
    'tertiary__expanded_spotfeatures_avg_intensity' : 'avg intensity',  # average intensity
    'tertiary__expanded_n2_avg' : 'n2 avg',  # normalised average intensity
    'tertiary__expanded_spotfeatures_count' : 'spot count'})  # number of spots

df_feats['spot density'] = (df_feats['spot count'] / df_feats['roi size'])  # spots per area

1. Comparison of DSB detection approachesÂ¶

1.1 Compare spot density and granulometry featuresÂ¶

We see a strong correlation between measuring normalised spot count and a granulometry-based approach.

In [7]:
plot = df_feats.groupby('well')[['spot density', 'granulometry (3)']].mean().reset_index()

sns.regplot('spot density', 'granulometry (3)', data=plot, fit_reg=True, scatter_kws={'s': 5})
corr = np.corrcoef(plot['spot density'], plot['granulometry (3)'])[0, 1]
sns.plt.title(r'Spot density vs. granulometry (2) ($\rho=%0.2f$)' % corr)
plt.show()

The curve artefacts at the base of the cloud are the result of computing spot density on cells with a single spot, two spots, etc., giving density = $\frac{1}{area}$, $\frac{2}{area}$, etc. as area is fairly constant across cells.

2.3 Spot distribution in low-cell-count wellsÂ¶

In [29]:
THRESHOLD = 20
feature = 'spot density'

df_cell_counts = df_feats.groupby('well')['cell count'].count().reset_index()
low_count_wells = df_cell_counts[df_cell_counts['cell count'] < THRESHOLD]['well'].tolist()

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)
df_plot_low = df_feats[df_feats['well'].isin(low_count_wells)]
sns.distplot(df_plot_low[feature], ax=ax)
plt.title('Cell count: %d' % df_plot_low.shape[0])

ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)
df_plot_high = df_feats[~df_feats['well'].isin(low_count_wells)].sample(n=df_plot_low.shape[0])
sns.distplot(df_plot_high[feature], ax=ax)
plt.title('Cell count: %d' % df_plot_high.shape[0])

plt.show()
In [30]:
stats.kolmogorov_smirnov(df_plot_low[feature], df_plot_high[feature])
Out[30]:
0.0035699117672271731

Despite the possible confounding factor, exchangeability appears not to have been violated on low-cell-count wells.

2.3 Results by spot countÂ¶

We proceed with the spot count approach:

In [31]:
df_non_dmso = df_feats[~df_feats['content'].isin(['DMSO', 'None'])]
df_dmso = df_feats[df_feats['content'] == 'DMSO']
df_empty = df_feats[df_feats['content'] == 'None']

BONFERRONI_THRESHOLD = stats.P_VALUE_THRESHOLD / len(df_non_dmso['well'].unique())

We use a K-S test to compare with the negative control, with a Bonferonni correction on a 0.01 p-value threshold. Note this is an especially conservative correction.

In [32]:
feature = 'spot count'

df_p_scores = df_non_dmso.groupby('well')[feature].agg(
    lambda x: stats.kolmogorov_smirnov(df_dmso[feature], x)).reset_index()

df_p_scores[df_p_scores[feature] < BONFERRONI_THRESHOLD].sort_values(feature).reset_index()

Where $B$ is the distribution of double strand breaks in the well, $D$ is the amount of cell death, $C$ is the ultimate cell count and $P$ is the p-value statistic calculated in the analysis. The structure renders $B$ a confounder, hence it must be conditioned on prior to analysis. As a continuous-valued variable, it must be thresholded somehow, the simplest approach being a binary threshold.

In [36]:
CONFOUNDER_THRESHOLD = 200  # threshold on cell count
feature = 'spot count'
In [37]:
df_count = df_non_dmso.groupby('well')['cell count'].count().reset_index()
low_cell_count_wells = df_count[df_count['cell count'] <= CONFOUNDER_THRESHOLD]['well'].as_matrix()
high_cell_count_wells = df_count[df_count['cell count'] > CONFOUNDER_THRESHOLD]['well'].as_matrix()

LOW_CELL_BONFERRONI_THRESHOLD = stats.P_VALUE_THRESHOLD / len(low_cell_count_wells)
HIGH_CELL_BONFERRONI_THRESHOLD = stats.P_VALUE_THRESHOLD / len(high_cell_count_wells)

df_low = df_feats[df_feats['well'].isin(low_cell_count_wells)]
df_high = df_feats[df_feats['well'].isin(high_cell_count_wells)]
In [38]:
df_p_scores = df_low.groupby('well')[feature].agg(
    lambda x: stats.kolmogorov_smirnov(df_dmso[feature], x)).reset_index()
k = stats.benjamini_hochberg(df_p_scores[feature])
df_p_scores.sort_values(feature).reset_index().head(k)

2.5 Link to DAPI channelÂ¶

In Perelman et al. (2004), they note, ``At low concentrations, the histogram for the total DNA content has the characteristic bimodal shape reflecting a mixture of G1, S, and G2/M cell populations. G2 and M populations may be distinguished by 2D display of total DNA signal against nuclear area (25).'' (page 2)

In [40]:
# Clip extreme outliers for better clustering
THRESHOLD = 350000
df_feats['total intensity'] = df_feats['primary__primary4_n2_avg'] * df_feats['roi size']
df_threshold = df_feats[df_feats['total intensity'] < THRESHOLD]
